<h2><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Four_Noble_Truths&amp;action=edit&amp;section=5" title="Edit section: Notes">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline">Notes</span></h2>
<div class="references-small">
<ol class="references">
<li id="cite_note-0"><b><a href="#cite_ref-0" title="">^</a></b> Duff (2008), p. 17</li>
<li id="cite_note-1"><b><a href="#cite_ref-1" title="">^</a></b> Nanamoli (1995), p. 106</li>
<li id="cite_note-2"><b><a href="#cite_ref-2" title="">^</a></b> Harvey (1990), p. 92.</li>
<li id="cite_note-3"><b><a href="#cite_ref-3" title="">^</a></b> Gethin (1998), p. 60.</li>
<li id="cite_note-shramana-4">^ <a href="#cite_ref-shramana_4-0" title=""><sup><i><b>a</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-shramana_4-1" title=""><sup><i><b>b</b></i></sup></a> Warder (1970), p. 34.</li>
<li id="cite_note-5"><b><a href="#cite_ref-5" title="">^</a></b> The term used by the Buddha is <a href="/wiki/Dukkha" title="Dukkha">dukkha</a>. While <a href="/wiki/Suffering" title="Suffering">suffering</a> – i.e., being in a state of physical or mental pain – is one aspect of dukkha, it is believed by many that suffering is too narrow a translation and that it is best to leave dukkha untranslated.</li>
<li id="cite_note-6"><b><a href="#cite_ref-6" title="">^</a></b> Nanamoli (1995), p. 1856.</li>
<li id="cite_note-7"><b><a href="#cite_ref-7" title="">^</a></b> Nanamoli (1995), pp. 533-36.</li>
<li id="cite_note-BodhiDhammacakka-8">^ <a href="#cite_ref-BodhiDhammacakka_8-0" title=""><sup><i><b>a</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-BodhiDhammacakka_8-1" title=""><sup><i><b>b</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-BodhiDhammacakka_8-2" title=""><sup><i><b>c</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-BodhiDhammacakka_8-3" title=""><sup><i><b>d</b></i></sup></a> <a href="/wiki/Dhammacakkappavattana_Sutta" title="Dhammacakkappavattana Sutta">Dhammacakkappavattana Sutta</a> (<a href="/wiki/Samyutta_Nikaya" title="Samyutta Nikaya">SN</a> 56.11), trans. Bodhi (2000), pp. 1843-47.</li>
<li id="cite_note-ChineseBodhiDhammacakka-9">^ <a href="#cite_ref-ChineseBodhiDhammacakka_9-0" title=""><sup><i><b>a</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-ChineseBodhiDhammacakka_9-1" title=""><sup><i><b>b</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-ChineseBodhiDhammacakka_9-2" title=""><sup><i><b>c</b></i></sup></a> <cite style="font-style:normal" class="web"><a href="http://w3.cbeta.org/result/normal/T02/0109_001.htm" class="external text" title="http://w3.cbeta.org/result/normal/T02/0109_001.htm" rel="nofollow">"轉法輪經"</a>. Cbeta<span class="printonly">. <a href="http://w3.cbeta.org/result/normal/T02/0109_001.htm" class="external free" title="http://w3.cbeta.org/result/normal/T02/0109_001.htm" rel="nofollow">http://w3.cbeta.org/result/normal/T02/0109_001.htm</a></span><span class="reference-accessdate">. Retrieved on 2008-10-28</span>.</cite><span class="Z3988" title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=bookitem&amp;rft.btitle=%E8%BD%89%E6%B3%95%E8%BC%AA%E7%B6%93&amp;rft.atitle=&amp;rft.pub=Cbeta&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Fw3.cbeta.org%2Fresult%2Fnormal%2FT02%2F0109_001.htm&amp;rfr_id=info:sid/en.wikipedia.org:Four_Noble_Truths"><span style="display: none;">&#160;</span></span></li>
<li id="cite_note-10"><b><a href="#cite_ref-10" title="">^</a></b> <a href="/wiki/Samyutta_Nikaya" title="Samyutta Nikaya">SN</a> 56.11, trans. Bodhi (2000), p. 1844. In this translation, Bodhi elides the six middle factors of the Noble Eightfold Path (between right view and right concentration). Thus Bodhi's translation for the six middle factors was taken from his translation of <a href="/wiki/Samyutta_Nikaya" title="Samyutta Nikaya">SN</a> 45.1 (Bodhi, 2000, p. 1523-24). See also Feer (1976), p. 421f.</li>
<li id="cite_note-11"><b><a href="#cite_ref-11" title="">^</a></b> In <a href="/wiki/Anguttara_Nikaya" title="Anguttara Nikaya">AN</a> 3.61, the Buddha provides an alternate elaboration on the second and third noble truths identifying the arising and cessation of suffering in accordance with <a href="/wiki/Pratitya-samutpada" title="Pratitya-samutpada" class="mw-redirect">Dependent Origination</a>'s <a href="/wiki/Twelve_Nidanas" title="Twelve Nidanas" class="mw-redirect">Twelve Causes</a>, from <a href="/wiki/Avidya_(Buddhism)" title="Avidya (Buddhism)" class="mw-redirect">ignorance</a> to <a href="/wiki/Jaramarana" title="Jaramarana" class="mw-redirect">old age and death</a> <a href="http://www.accesstoinsight.org/tipitaka/an/an03/an03.061.than.html" class="external text" title="http://www.accesstoinsight.org/tipitaka/an/an03/an03.061.than.html" rel="nofollow">(Thanissaro, 1997).</a></li>
</ol>
</div>
